nt and did not interfere with the exercises, but some fathers were left - as it later turned out - to &quot;cheer&quot; on their kids. I don\'t mind cheering if the cheering is actually cheering and not something else that we\'ll find out in a moment.\r\nI took the ball out of the holder and started to warm up - I saw how once the kids, once the parents, looked at me in disbelief, &quot;what\'s the best he is doing&quot;. By the way - I like being looked at - then I have more pressure, which I turn into a desire to play even better. After about 30 minutes, I was literally gasping like a dragon that needed water - I needed it badly too, but of course, I didn\'t take it from her room - all me. Then I took a three-minute rest - I stood at the pole and, watching the players, I analyzed the situation on the pitch.\r\n- They play the game, seven against seven, some in blue shirts, others in yellow, it\'s 2: 1.\r\nThe coach was telling both teams with his loud voice - it\'s nice that he is so involved in what he does. However, sometimes his voice was muffled by several other voices - I do not mean the young representatives of Poland, but their dear fathers.\r\nYes, FATHERS.\r\nIf I was in their shoes, every now and then I would try to support my son with words like &quot;come on, give&quot;, &quot;you almost shot, great&quot;, &quot;gool, bravo!&quot;\r\nFor this they were yelling and shouting:\r\n- Play passes, you won\'t hit yourself,\r\n- Remember what I told you, don\'t play like that,\r\n- It\'s good that they shot you,\r\n- Why are you playing so poorly,\r\nAnd many other similarly &quot;motivating&quot; phrases.\r\nI felt sorry for these children that they had to fulfil their parents\' unfulfilled dreams. Yes, in my opinion, this was the situation. It was evident that some of the kids were playing under pressure, not enjoying or enjoying the sport. If I were the trainer, I would make the rule that parents cannot stay during training. Just for such situations.\r\nChildren are taught this constant pressure from an early age, the stress from a lost action, from a wasted corner, from not scoring a goal, from a bad pass. These shouts are not good for them - they finally came to have fun, rest after school, about which I will not even comment, because this is not what this entry is about.\r\nTraining - yes - should teach you how to play better and develop better, but not in this way. I helped many people to do the first around the world - I was always passionate and, above all, that the player would enjoy it, I gave him words of encouragement, and finally, he did it and then I was happy with the small goal achieved with him.\r\nThe only thing I want to ask you is not to do something similar to anyone - you already know how it can end for the other person.\r\nBut the parents know better...'),(3865,55,277,'tandc','1'),(3866,55,277,'privacy-cookie','1'),(3867,55,277,'g-recaptcha-response','03AGdBq27qLbYQH2lD3UZPktpruq3ZPYi-r2y_qkARUK7MPsRfjokkO9n7TzfM382fhdoR9wI6mqXUsdaIg8BJ-rH_KlzcNJIQ7GW77EtmBTG_MPLpdbIbHIzU2OrKQU3F7YJiKjBJP-FQ_rFyA11zDqzRWKXCqnpT3noSSyM0w7aJBKb14Nr0LBbAKmbXboEABguzuQhWKIHUmMtYlb-x8WB1dRTnEpbCuNeUH6Bw5Uv620VpvHsPOUkHQ0JSQtuqcywtwIqCJuZQpEoqVjlAnw6jYwJsCXbigqHsr2IfZPevKoiuEcF4Es0bPJJhg9S30r19GDi0yMFfhWgIFF9Z9uejXyw5GmG-GWvEHHwrYdfFUKeThnF7bxOBryqxN7etMdCdYymZEsuGc7RwGYOhuGr1FakWP5rqRxDHcBTg-GshPpKQD9uzivB_mW_w7cTuH7UtB2pN26ensEpXEAtsjSa4BT59_UfiKNF7dFGj1NSxi1jVfpIh8i_PUWXUlncPkez9KB3l9Q4adJlGNoe8z2DcUChDcWmPyA'),(3868,55,277,'submit_time','2020-10-29 22:25:40'),(3869,55,277,'submit_ip','81.128.188.150'),(3870,55,278,'first-name','Matthew '),(3871,55,278,'last-name','Saul Hart'),(3872,55,278,'contact-number','07588358146'),(3873,55,278,'email-add','karensurtees1@gmail.com'),(3874,55,278,'birth-date','2012-06-04'),(3875,55,278,'address-1','46 parkgate lane'),(3876,55,278,'town-city','Blaydon Tyne and wear '),(3877,55,278,'postcode','Ne216qq '),(3878,55,278,'your-story','I nominate my grandson Matty. He would be my phone