d betting is my hobby I use to play football and from there this passion. For watching football my wife is angry sometimes i hope im the winner  yupii yupii thank you and god bless you \";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-29 22:12:02'),(281,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:6:\"Viktor\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:6:\"Sandor\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07856361977\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:24:\"viktorsandor90@gmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:18:\"57 Galloway street\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:9:\"Liverpool\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:6:\"L7 6PD\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-29 22:14:36'),(282,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:6:\"Steven\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:6:\"Hughes\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07455466057\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:28:\"stevenhughes1976@hotmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1975-11-26\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:16:\"63 Osborne road \";s:9:\"town-city\";s:11:\"Hartlepool \";s:8:\"postcode\";s:9:\"TS26 9JN \";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-29 22:22:34'),(283,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:8:\"Slawomir\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:9:\"Laskowski\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07827229114\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:30:\"slawomir.laskowski@yahoo.co.uk\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1980-12-02\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:14:\"48 Norman Lane\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:10:\"Swanscombe\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:8:\"DA10 1EL\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:4516:\"Football is currently the most popular team sport in the world. Every boy dreams of playing for one of the great teams in the future and becoming a football idol. From an early age, we watch football stars on television, who charm on the pitch with their skills - once Zidane, Ronaldinho, now Robert Lewandowski or Lionel Messi.\r\nAnd it all started in ...\r\nAs usual, I entered the boarding school, threw my backpack, read a few pages of the book that I had received for my birthday, I wore black shorts that did not reach the knees, worn blue pumas and was ready to go to my dream training. Just the ball and it&#039;s ready - I opened the wardrobe in which I keep it, leaned over and picked it up - it was sitting obediently in the holder.\r\n- I&#039;m going to play if someone calls you will say that then I&#039;ll call okay? - I said to the buddies from the room.\r\n- Oh for sure! One of them said.\r\nI closed the door and started toward the field.\r\nI do not like going with my phone and a watch for training - I have noticed that when I have a time-measuring device, it is worse for me to focus on training and therefore I look at my P8 Lite more often to see how much I play if it is an hour I am finished. I don&#039;t know why I did, but I try to wean myself from it and play without a watch until my body is no longer able to hold it and is on the verge of exhaustion.\r\nOn the pitch, to my surprise, there were not too big children - probably up to 10-11 years old. They were just starting training - not all of them were there yet because my parents would bring another little player with their ball every few minutes. Almost all of the parents (especially mothers) went and did not interfere with the exercises, but some fathers were left - as it later turned out - to &quot;cheer&quot; on their kids. I don&#039;t mind cheering if the cheering is actually cheering and not something else that we&#039;ll find out in a moment.\r\nI took the ball out of the holder and started to warm up - I saw how once the kids, once the parents, looked at me in disbelief, &quot;what&#039;s the best he is doing&quot;. By the way - I like being looked at - then I have more pressure, which I turn into a desire to play even better. After about 30 minutes, I was literally gasping like a dragon that needed water - I needed it badly too, but of course, I didn&#039;t take it from her room - all me. Then I took a three-minute rest - I stood at the pole and, watching the players, I analyzed the situation on the pitch.\r\n- They play the game, seven against seven, some in blue shirts, others in yellow, it&#039;s 2: 1.\r\nThe coach was telling both teams with his loud voice - it&#039;s nice that he is so involved in what he does. However, sometimes his voice was muffled by several other voices - I do not mean the young representatives of Poland, but their dear fathers.\r\nYes, FATHERS.\r\nIf I was in their shoes, every now and then I would try to support my son with words like &quot;come on, give&quot;, &quot;you almost shot, great&quot;, &quot;gool, bravo!&quot;\r\nFor this they were yelling and shouting:\r\n- Play passes, you won&#039;t hit yourself,\r\n- Remember what I told you, don&#039;t play like that,\r\n- It&#039;s good that they shot you,\r\n- Why are you playing so poorly,\r\nAnd many other similarly &quot;motivating&quot; phrases.\r\nI felt sorry for these children that they had to fulfil their parents&#039; unfulfilled dreams. Yes, in my opinion, this was the situation. It was evident that some of the kids were playing under pressure, not enjoying or enjoying the sport. If I were the trainer, I would make the rule that parents cannot stay during training. Just for such situations.\r\nChildren are taught this constant pressure from an early age, the stress from a lost action, from a wasted corner, from not scoring a goal, from a bad pass. These shouts are not good for them - they finally came to have fun, rest after school, about which I will not even comment, because this is not what this entry is about.\r\nTraining - yes - should teach you how to play better and develop better, but not in this way. I helped many people to do the first around the world - I was always passionate and, above all, that the player would enjoy it, I gave him words of encouragement, and finally, he did it and then I was happy w