\"\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:6:\"ilford\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:6:\"london\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:6:\"ig11tl\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-30 16:41:23'),(385,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:4:\"Greg\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:6:\"Robson\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07798580899\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:28:\"ellen.robson1@btinternet.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1966-11-02\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:22:\"Crathorne House Lodge \";s:9:\"town-city\";s:5:\"Yarm \";s:8:\"postcode\";s:8:\"TS15 9LL\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:4095:\"I&#039;m nominating my dad, Greg Robson, to be football fan of the year.\r\n\r\nMy Dad&#039;s football obsession started long before I was born- as a youngster he played in the Northern League and did a stint of time playing in the States. Despite enjoying this, he realised in his mid 20&#039;s that it was time for him to get what he thought was a &#039;real job&#039; and came home to the UK. \r\n\r\nBeing born and raised in Teesside, just like me, my dad has always been an avid Middlesbrough fan, has had a season ticket for as long as I can remember and has attended every game he could in times when the pay check couldn&#039;t quite stretch for a season ticket; even throughout the pandemic he has been tuning into the games via his little laptop and cheering on the Boro. \r\nHe started taking me to the Boro matches when I was around 15 and was the reason I became a boro fan too!\r\n\r\nDespite not having made it as a football player, he has always done his best to incorporate his passion for football into his occupation. His last job, with a company which worked with the Sunderland FC Foundation of Light, enabled him to help those most deprived in the Sunderland community, providing them with a better education and teaching the unemployed the skills they needed to get a job. The involvement of Sunderland FC allowed the strong influence of the club upon the local community to reach those most in need, with participants respecting and understanding the programme because of the involvement of the football club and it&#039;s meaning to the community. He also initiated contact with Middlesbrough FC to help further their foundation. \r\nThis meant he got to meet the players of the Sunderland team quite often- on one trip to his company&#039;s base in Sunderland, the team were having a hard season and had barely won any games. My Dad understood that it was important for the players to take time away from the intense football environment and just chill out for the day, experiencing something new. The next Sunderland match 2 days later, Sunderland won 4-1, with my Dad and his team knowing that their day with the Sunderland lads had influenced them in a good way (and maybe even was the reason they won the match!)\r\n\r\nhttps:&#047;&#047;www.safc.com&#047;news&#047;club-news&#047;2018&#047;march&#047;team-visits-caterpillar\r\n2.37-2.51 minutes on video- My dad was the only one who scored (all the Sunderland players missed!) and Chris Coleman shook his hand and jokingly asked him to get his boots on for the next Sunderland match! \r\n\r\nNot only this, but Dad trained to be a youth football coach when my brother&#039;s football team lost their previous one because of his understanding of football&#039;s impact on the community and young people. He understood that the lads he coached loved their football team, what it meant to them, and that to lose the team would impact their development and their sense of belonging. \r\nIt required a lot of dedication and took up so much of his time, but it is something he still talks about today and I know that he secretly misses standing on the edge of a football pitch on a freezing cold Sunday morning, helping the lads to play their best. He coached my brother and his friends to an amazing standard (despite their cheekiness), leading to my brother being scouted by 2 different teams and offered places on their academy teams at the age of 12. \r\n\r\nI was born on the 1st September 2001, the same day and time which England beat Germany 5-1 in a world cup qualifier match- despite this being a huge day for him and all England fans, he still managed to make it in time to the hospital to see me being born! \r\n\r\nDad has always given my family everything we have needed and provided for us; there has never been a day which we have gone without and I will always be so grateful for my amazing upbringing. My Dad embodies everything which football stands for; community, dedication and collaboration. I believe that he deserves to win football fan of the year and that he would truly treasure and make the most of whatever he would win. \r\n\r\n\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-30 16:47:48'),(386,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:3:\"Lee\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:8:\"Boswell \";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:25:\"scottboswell557@gmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:0:\"\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:0:\"\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-30 17:10:21'),(387,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:4:\"Paul\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:6:\"Whomes\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07309712895\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:23:\"paulwhomes555@gmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:18:\"86 Winifred Street\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:6:\"London\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"E16 2HX\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-10-30 17:20:37'),(388,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:6:\"Patrik\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:5:\"Banda\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07443080244\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:29:\"patrikbanda29081986@gmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1986-08-29\";s: