\"town-city\";s:7:\"Glasgow\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:8:\"G52 4EL \";s:10:\"your-story\";s:757:\"When I was proposing to my now wife we always went to watch Celtic together home or away and had some fabulous trips to the Camp Nou, San Soro and Ajax of Amsterdam.I was looking for something special to propose and I thought I&#039;d get a plane over Celtic Park with Large letter saying Donna will you marry me love Chris.Her son Craig was taking flying lessons from Glasgow Airport and he put me on to a guy who could facilitate this. So it was all set Celtic were playing Stranraer in the Scottish Cup and the game was that boring she decided to go for a nap.As the plane came over at half time I had to nudge her and actually tell her to look up to the plane so the moral of the story is your better just taking your Mrs up in the plane and asking her.\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-03 17:11:08'),(563,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:7:\"Claire \";s:9:\"last-name\";s:8:\"Elliott \";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07730400500\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:24:\"claire@gregelliott.co.uk\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1968-08-02\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:21:\"84 Slatch House Road \";s:9:\"town-city\";s:9:\"Bearwood \";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"B67 5QB\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:5159:\"I am nominating Steven Green. \r\nHe is a Wolves fan who is paralysed from the neck down who still makes it to nearly all of Wolves Home and Away games. \r\nSteve also made it to many of our Europa games in places like Istanbul (where he had to be pushed uphill in his wheelchair) and Braga where he was in his wheelchair was carried over the boggy field, in torrential rain,  dodging extremely unfriendly, baton wielding, riot happy policemen. \r\n\r\nSteve was paralysed from the chest down in 2011 whilst serving in the RAF in a freak accident. \r\n\r\nThe motorbike he had bought was faulty, and unbeknown to Steve, should never have been sold to him. He was driving at normal speeds when a witness reported that the bike juddered, threw him off and into a road sign resulting in him being multiply injured, unconscious and fighting for his life. \r\n\r\nSteve had a wife, Mari, also a fanatical wolves fan and a daughter Lucia. She was heavily pregnant with their son Carlos at the time. I was birth partner for Mari in July 2011 when Carlos was born as Steve was too unwell to attend his own sons birth. \r\n\r\n\r\nAlthough they are now divorced, its a measure of what wonderful people they are that they still attend games together as a family unit. \r\n\r\nSteves tragic accident and resultant paralysis was also a catalyst for some good. His Father, Dennis Green, also a Wolves season ticket holder helped set up the Wolves DSA. \r\n\r\nAs part of the Wolves family, A few of us realised how difficult the situation was for Mari. She had a husband in hospital two hours away from where she lived, was 7 months pregnant and had a four year old to care for. \r\n\r\nWe wanted to do something for them as a family so that Mari could stay in a hotel near Steve and not have to worry about petrol and hotel costs.\r\n\r\nWe held the Steve Green Fundraiser, predominantly a football match on 23rdJuly 2011 at Tipton Town FC. \r\n\r\nWolves printed off the tickets, Wolfie attended, We had the FA Cup on loan, Tipton Town let us use their facilities free of charge, former Wolves Players John Richards, Mel Eves, Robbie Dennison, Andy Thompson Matt Murray(and others) attended with John Richards kicking off the game.\r\n\r\n\r\n Steve Saul helped organise an auction in the evening. We raised a four figure sum to help Mari, Steve, Lucia and Carlos. \r\n\r\nSteve was in hospital for over a year and continued his rehabilitation in Headley Court. \r\n\r\nSteve learnt to drive in a specially adapted car and went back to work. He continues to attend wolves games home and away even though he lives in Wiltshire which is no mean feat in itself. \r\n\r\nTravelling with Steve, makes you realise how much you take getting to games for granted.\r\n Steve has to wheel himself to his car, use a special slide board to get in, then disassemble the chair and put it in the car, only to reverse the process when he arrives at Molineux. \r\n\r\nWhen its pouring with rain, you and I can shelter-but he has to try and get the process done as quickly as possible. The effort, just to get into his car, to get to games is amazing. \r\n\r\nSteve is at risk of chest infections and pneumonia due to his condition, this is often life-limiting. \r\n\r\n Until Steve  had major surgery 7 weeks ago had only only missed one game this year home and away. \r\n\r\nOne of the side effects of being paralysed is that you dont have sensation when you get a wound. You dont shuffle around when you should to ease pressure on skin. Pressure sores occur. These can be fatal, particularly if infected. \r\n\r\nAs Steve now lives in his own, theres no one to tell him he has a wound, to nip things in the bud and get the medical attention his wound needed. \r\n\r\nSteve developed a huge pressure area which you could put your fist in. This required intricate surgery to repair muscles in his thigh and a skin graft. \r\n\r\nSteve was not allowed to get out of bed for several weeks in case the wound broke down. To begin with he could only lie flat and then gradually raise his head. \r\n\r\nYesterday he got a pass from Salisbury hospital to go to the match at Wembley in the strict proviso that he went back to bedrest today. \r\n\r\nOf course we are all gutted about the result, but for Steve, he is living with his life-limiting paralysis every day, with very little complaint. He is inspirational the way he continues to attend wolves games, be as independent as possible and care for his children.\r\n\r\nHe loves the Wolves and Im pretty sure that our current team, owners and manager have helped him get through these dark hours. Its given him something to look forward to-something to work towards. \r\n\r\nOne of the saddest things Steve said to me, was that he was unable to kick a ball around with his son, Carlos. He saw that as a failing, a shortcoming of his role as a Father, unable to knock a football around with his son, like his Dad did. \r\n\r\nYesterday, his children sat with him at Wembley. The result may not have gone our way, but that is a small part of the picture when you look at the extended Wolves Family. \r\n\r\nThis is Steves address-\r\n28 Calne road, Lyneham, Chippenham, Wiltshire,  SN15 4PT\r\nHe can be contacted on +44 7588 771012\r\n\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-03 17:47:05'),(564,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:7:\"Tamisha\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:8:\"Saunders\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07311362245\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:23:\"tamisha2015@outlook.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1992-02-25\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:15:\"501 Pearl Court\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:7:\"Ipswich\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"IP2 8FG\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:616:\"My husband of 10 years darron peck is the most biggest fan of football and life long Alan Shearer mega fan from childhood along side his father Roy peck whos mother is a true geordie born, bread and just sadly berried all the way from Ipswich we made sure our true geordie queen made it home as she wished ! \r\nI no that This would mean the absolute world to my husband His a true NUFC fan and names Alan Shearer his football legend hero .... \r\nSo to say my husband and his family of four generations are truly and utterly dedicated to football but there is only ONE TEAM FOR USE!! Through and through Newcastle !!\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-03 18:00:29'),(565,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:5:\"Simon\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:9:\"Kennerley\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07768479932\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:27:\"simon_kennerley@hotmail.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1964-03-23\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:13:\"21 ABBOTS WAY\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:13:\"Knaresborough\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"HG5 8EU\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:2674:\"I wish to nominate my middle son, Ross Kennerley.\r\n\r\nFrom 1996 until 2009 our family lived in Malmo, Sweden where we moved for my work. It was a tough time for all of us especially in the early years, but we had an escape which was that Sweden could show up to 5 PL matches in a weekend.\r\n\r\nRoss was only 3 when we moved so had no allegiance to any particular team (my wife, Amanda and I have been lifetime York City fans) so his love of a team came, as so many in Scandinavia do, from watching English football.\r\n\r\nThat team was Arsenal, and it has become an obsession.\r\n\r\nI used to fly with him back to the UK to see matches for birthdays, and when funds allowed, the first being Middlesborough away (0-1, Henry). He became a Junior Gunner and still holds Silver Membership.\r\n\r\nWhen we moved back to England, Ross did A-levels, failed horribly, dusted himself down and went to college to do a media studies course and got a DDM and won a 1000 scholarship to Northumbria University to study Journalism, specialising in Sports Journalism. After 3 years he graduated but found paid work hard to find though he did a number of internships including by glorious irony, working for the York Evening Press reporting on York City.\r\n\r\nEventually he got an opening which meant he could go to Prague for 3 months on the Erasmus program, where he reported on a variety of sports for an English language paper.\r\n\r\nHis break came after he returned and moved to London with his girlfriend whom he met in Prague. Whilst working as a waiter he applied for as many journalism  jobs as he could and eventually was offered a 3 month trial with a football website called 90min.com. They took him on part-time and he continued to work in the restaurant, until very recently when 90min offered him the chance go full time as Site Expert for a part of their group, a site entirely dedicated to the team he loves, called paininthearsenal.com  \r\n\r\nAfter a lot of sacrifice and hard work, he is now living the dream, writing, opining and talking everything Arsenal.\r\n\r\nJust as an aside, whilst this is about Ross, last year I visited different ground number 101, Billingham Synthosia (paid to get in, got free tickets or as in the case of Bath City v York City, blagged in for free carrying a badminton racquet - but that&#039;s a different story). These 101 come from 8 different countries, and includes  the Bernabeu, which is particularly interesting as both Amanda and I have been there, but not together. Perhaps I should nominate all 3 of us? If I throw in that 14 years ago I had a heart transplant, might that add a little pathos? It also links directly to the badminton racquet story.\r\n\r\n\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-03 18:23:46'),(566,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:5:\"Craig\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:7:\"Findlay\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07902387076\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:25:\"craigfindlay635@yahoo.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1978-05-07\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:12:\"10 rushhill \";s:9:\"town-city\";s:3:\"Ayr\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"Ka7 3xy\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-03 18:42:47'),(567,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:4:\"Gary\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:6:\"Gibson\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:20:\"pipa08@hotmail.co.uk\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1980-09-09\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:26:\"24 Roche avenue, Belfarm, \";s:9:\"town-city\";s:4:\"York\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:8:\"Yo31 9bb\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:1154:\"Gary is my older brother, he has loved football from a very young age though hes now 40yrs old. He would go and watch Scarborough play with my late Grand