ndc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-04 08:25:00'),(575,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:11:\"Nicolangelo\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:9:\"Marrafino\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07513461480\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:32:\"nicolangelomarrafino@yahoo.co.uk\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1981-02-09\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:19:\"6 b Chesterton road\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:6:\"London\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"W10 5lx\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:113:\"My son is very passionate about football. He watches every game from every league in every country in the world. \";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-04 11:30:10'),(576,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:3:\"Joe\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:4:\"Bass\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07834235396\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:22:\"j.a.bass@hotmail.co.uk\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1958-10-17\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:21:\"166 Grange Rd, Newark\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:5:\"Notts\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:8:\"NG24 4PP\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:3963:\"I have followed the England football team since I was seventeen\r\nbut it was only later in life, at 51, when I started to attend tournaments.  I could never before afford it on a window -cleaner&#039;s income, having a mortgage and two kids.  But once I had shaken off those shackles I was free to fly.  And I did.  South Africa was my first tournament in 2014, and being a hopeless optimist, expecting England to win the World Cup, got tickets all the way to the final. \r\nMy wife thought I was mad, going at age, on my own, using public transport, staying in tents and grubby hostels, well aware of the horrendous crime rate of SA and expecting me to return with bits of my anatomy missing.\r\nOne of my customers showed me a newspaper clipping citing the appalling crime statistics of SA.  But I would not be dissuaded.  I was only 51, not yet a dinosaur, and not yet ready to stay permanently at home, feeding the goldfish, watching the Last of the Summer Wine.\r\n\r\nI was going with a definite aim and attitude.  I was going to travel light, cheap and solo.  I would make the best of things, adapt quickly, ask for help (you nearly always get it) and give help.  By travelling solo I would be more approachable, better able to engage the locals and the foreign fan, something I was determined to do.  (I doubt very much that family in Manaus would have invited me to stay in their home for two days if I was in a group, when I was turned away from an over-booked hotel.  Or maybe they would have done!)\r\n\r\nThe team stuttered and fell out the sky.  The Germans in Bloemfontein trampled their muddy boots all over my dreams.\r\nI was gutted, we were out. But it was too late, I was hooked.  I was addicted.  I had loved it all, despite a few scares, including being surrounded my hungry baboons while cycling just outside Cape Town.  I had loved the friendliness of everyone, the safari park, the travelling by bus everywhere.\r\n\r\nThe Euros in 2016 were next and, with the vuvelezas of Cape Town still ringing in my ears, travelled to Ukraine.  That too ended in tears.  But there were good memories too, including being treated like a king by gold-toothed miners in Donetsk and a boat journey up the Dnieper.\r\n\r\nThen it was the World Cup in Brazil and another blow to our footballing prestige when we were eliminated at the second match.  It didn&#039;t help my mood that someone cloned my card and 2000 vanished into the electronic ether, leaving me with just 1.45 in my account, with two weeks left.  Then returning to London to find my car too had vanished into the ether.\r\n\r\nBut there had been good times too. Once I got hopelessly lost in a favela in Rio and was almost taken by the hand and shown the way out by the locals.  Then visiting the El Christo statue, watching Brazil play on one of the giant screens erected on Copacabana, till long after midnight.  And going on a boat journey up the Rio Negra at the jungle city of Manaus, with the family who had rescued me from my bedless state.\r\n\r\nThen it was the World Cup in Russia, when I was finally able to  forgive the England team all its past wrongs.  I went to all seven games, visiting six cities in the process.  I travelled 7594 kms by air and 6716kms by train.  I high-fived at least 80 volunteers, slept an average of 4 hours a night, lost 3 pairs of glasses , 5 pairs of socks, a pair of shoes and a box of cornflakes.\r\n\r\nAnd again, I loved it all.  Well, nearly all.  I didn&#039;t think much to the 26 hour train journey to Novograd only to discover my hostel was at another Novograd a 1000 miles away.  But was soon happy again when a Russian couple offered me their spare room above their tattoo shop at a very cheap rate.  The highlights of that trip?  Visiting the Mother of Russia monument in Volgograd and Gorky Park in Moscow - and oh yes, the penalty shoot-out against Columbia.\r\n\r\nI loved it all because all the world is truly united for four weeks watching and playing football.\r\n\r\n\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-04 12:50:28'),(577,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:6:\"unread\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:6:\"martyn\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:4:\"cook\";s:14:\"contact-number\";s:11:\"07983662271\";s:9:\"email-add\";s:20:\"cook-martin3@sky.com\";s:10:\"birth-date\";s:10:\"1970-12-05\";s:9:\"address-1\";s:18:\"254 dill hall lane\";s:9:\"town-city\";s:10:\"Accrington\";s:8:\"postcode\";s:7:\"bb5 4dg\";s:10:\"your-story\";s:217:\"I&#039;m a recovering alcoholic of 7years things have certainly been a test in recent months with lockdown luckily I&#039;ve worked through being groundsman at accrington Stanley fc.. Massive liverpool fan though YNWA\";s:5:\"tandc\";s:1:\"1\";s:14:\"privacy-cookie\";s:1:\"1\";}','2020-11-04 13:25:52'),(578,55,'a:12:{s:12:\"cfdb7_status\";s:4:\"read\";s:10:\"first-name\";s:5:\"Jamie\";s:9:\"last-name\";s:5:\"Scott\";s:14:\"contac